name: brew-rm

name: brew-update
description: Fetch the newest version of Homebrew and all formulae from GitHub using `git` and perform any necessary migrations. To upgrade all installed formulae, use `brew upgrade`. More information: <https://docs.brew.sh/Manpage#update-up-options>.

name: brew-upgrade
description: Upgrade outdated formulae and casks. More information: <https://docs.brew.sh/Manpage#upgrade-options-installed_formulainstalled_cask->.

name: bridge
description: Show and manipulate network bridge addresses and devices. More information: <https://manned.org/bridge>.

name: brightness
description: Get and set the brightness level of all internal and certain external displays. More information: <https://github.com/nriley/brightness>.

name: brightnessctl
description: Utility for reading and controlling device brightness for Linux operating systems. More information: <https://github.com/Hummer12007/brightnessctl#usage>.

name: brittany
description: Pretty-print Haskell source files. More information: <https://github.com/lspitzner/brittany#readme>.

name: broot
description: Navigate directory trees interactively. More information: <https://github.com/Canop/broot>.

name: brotli

name: browser-sync

name: browsh

name: bru

name: brushtopbm

name: bshell

name: bspc
description: Configure and control `bspwm`, managing nodes, desktops, monitors, and more. See also: `bspwm`. More information: <https://github.com/baskerville/bspwm/blob/master/doc/bspwm.1.asciidoc>.

name: bspwm
description: A tiling window manager based on binary space partitioning. See also: `bspc` for controlling it. More information: <https://github.com/baskerville/bspwm/blob/master/doc/bspwm.1.asciidoc>.

name: bssh
description: A GUI tool for browsing for SSH/VNC servers on the local network. See also: `bvnc`, `bshell`. More information: <https://manned.org/bssh>.

name: bsub
description: Submit batch jobs to LSF (Load Sharing Facility) scheduler. More information: <https://www.ibm.com/docs/spectrum-lsf/latest?topic=reference-bsub>.

name: btm

name: btop
description: A resource monitor that shows information about the CPU, memory, disks, network, and processes. A C++ version of `bpytop`. See also: `btm`, `glances`, `atop`, `htop`, `top`. More information: <https://github.com/aristocratos/btop#command-line-options>.

name: btrbk
description: Create snapshots and remote backups of btrfs subvolumes. More information: <https://digint.ch/btrbk/doc/readme.html>.

name: btrfs
description: A filesystem based on the copy-on-write (COW) principle for Linux. Some subcommands such as `device` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs.html>.

name: btrfs-balance
description: Balance block groups on a btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-balance.html>.

name: btrfs-check
description: Check or repair a btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-check.html>.

name: btrfs-device
description: Manage devices in a btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-device.html>.

name: btrfs-filesystem
description: Manage btrfs filesystems. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-filesystem.html>.

name: btrfs-inspect-internal
description: Query internal information of a btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-inspect-internal.html>.

name: btrfs-property
description: Get, set, or list properties for a BTRFS filesystem object (files, directories, subvolumes, filesystems, or devices). More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-property.html>.

name: btrfs-rescue
description: Try to recover a damaged btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-rescue.html>.

name: btrfs-restore
description: Try to salvage files from a damaged btrfs filesystem. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-restore.html>.

name: btrfs-scrub
description: Scrub btrfs filesystems to verify data integrity. It is recommended to run a scrub once a month. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-scrub.html>.

name: btrfs-subvolume
description: Manage btrfs subvolumes and snapshots. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs-subvolume.html>.

name: btrfs-version
description: Display btrfs-progs version. More information: <https://btrfs.readthedocs.io/en/latest/btrfs.html>.

name: bugreport
description: Show an Android bug report. This command can only be used through `adb shell`. More information: <https://cs.android.com/android/platform/superproject/+/main:frameworks/native/cmds/bugreport>.

name: bugreportz
description: Generate a zipped Android bug report. This command can only be used through `adb shell`. More information: <https://cs.android.com/android/platform/superproject/+/main:frameworks/native/cmds/bugreportz>.

name: builtin
description: Execute shell builtins. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#index-builtin>.

name: buku
description: Browser-independent bookmark manager. More information: <https://github.com/jarun/Buku#usage>.

name: bully
description: Brute-force the WPS pin of a wireless access point. Necessary information must be gathered with `airmon-ng` and `airodump-ng` before using `bully`. More information: <https://salsa.debian.org/pkg-security-team/bully>.

name: bun
description: JavaScript runtime and toolkit. Includes a bundler, a test runner, and a package manager. More information: <https://bun.com/docs>.

name: bun-add
description: Modern JavaScript runtime, package manager, bundler, and test runner. Note: `a` can be used as an alias for `add`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs>.

name: bun-audit
description: Check installed packages for known security vulnerabilities. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/audit>.

name: bun-build
description: Bundle JavaScript and TypeScript files with Bun's fast native bundler. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/bundler>.

name: bun-c
description: This command is an alias of `bun create`.

name: bun-create
description: Create a new project from a template. Note: `c` can be used as an alias for `create`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/runtime/templating/create>.

name: bun-exec
description: Execute shell commands or script files using Bun's runtime. Note: When running from a shell, remember to escape quotes. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/runtime/shell>.

name: bun-feedback
description: Sends feedback to `Bun`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/feedback#use-bun-feedback>.

name: bun-i
description: This command is an alias of `bun install`.

name: bun-info
description: Display package metadata from the npm registry. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/info>.

name: bun-init
description: Scaffold an empty Bun project. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/runtime/templating/init>.

name: bun-install
description: Install JavaScript dependencies for a project from `package.json`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/install>.

name: bun-link
description: Bun command to register the current package as a linkable package. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/link>.

name: bun-list
description: This command is an alias of `bun pm ls`.

name: bun-outdated
description: List dependencies in your project that have newer versions available. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/outdated>.

name: bun-patch
description: Prepare a package for patching or generate a patch file. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/patch>.

name: bun-pm
description: A set of utilities for working with Bun's package manager. Some subcommands such as `pack`, `pkg` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm>.

name: bun-pm-bin
description: Display the path to `bin` directories. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm#bin>.

name: bun-pm-ls
description: List installed dependencies and their versions. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm#ls>.

name: bun-pm-migrate
description: Convert another package manager's lockfile to a Bun-compatible lockfile without installing anything. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm#migrate>.

name: bun-pm-pkg
description: Manage package.json data with `get`, `set`, `delete`, and `fix` operations. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm#pkg>.

name: bun-pm-version
description: Manage the `version` field in `package.json`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/pm#version>.

name: bun-remove
description: Remove a dependency from `package.json`. Note: `rm` can be used as an alias for `remove`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/remove>.

name: bun-rm
description: This command is an alias of `bun remove`.

name: bun-run
description: Execute a JavaScript/TypeScript file, or a script from `package.json`. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/runtime>.

name: bun-test
description: Run tests using Bun's built-in test runner. It is a fast, Jest-compatible test runner that looks for `*.test.ts` (and similar) files. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/test>.

name: bun-update
description: Update dependencies in a Bun project. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/update>.

name: bun-upgrade
description: Upgrade Bun to the latest version. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/installation#upgrading>.

name: bun-why
description: Explain why a package is installed by showing its dependency chain. More information: <https://bun.com/docs/pm/cli/why>.

name: bundle

description: Manipulate Android Application Bundles. More information: <https://developer.android.com/tools/bundletool>.

name: bundletool-validate
description: Manipulate Android Application Bundles. More information: <https://developer.android.com/tools/bundletool>.

name: bunx

name: bunzip2

name: bup

name: burpsuite

Linux distributions that use BusyBox will usually provide symlinks for all programs. More information: <https://www.busybox.net/downloads/BusyBox>.

name: bw

name: byobu

name: bzfgrep

name: bzip2recover

name: caffeinate

description: Prevent desktop idleness in full-screen mode. More information: <https://manned.org/caffeine>.

name: caja

name: cake

name: cal

name: calc
description: An interactive arbitrary-precision calculator in the terminal. More information: <https://manned.org/calc>.

name: calcurse
description: A text-based calendar and scheduling application. More information: <https://github.com/lfos/calcurse/blob/pu/doc/calcurse.1.txt>.

name: calendar
description: Display upcoming events from a calendar file. More information: <https://manned.org/calendar>.

name: calibre-server
description: A server application to distribute e-books over a network. Note: E-books must already be imported into the library using the GUI or the `calibredb` CLI. Part of the Calibre e-book library. More information: <https://manual.calibre-ebook.com/generated/en/calibre-server.html>.

name: calibredb
description: Manipulate an e-book database. Part of the Calibre e-book library. More information: <https://manual.calibre-ebook.com/generated/en/calibredb.html>.

name: caligula
description: A user-friendly, lightweight TUI for disk imaging. See also: `dd`. More information: <https://github.com/ifd3f/caligula>.

name: caller

name: calligraflow

name: calligrasheets
description: Calligra's spreadsheet application. See also: `calligraflow`, `calligrastage`, `calligrawords`. More information: <https://manned.org/calligrasheets>.

name: calligrastage

name: calligrawords
description: Calligra's word processor application. See also: `calligraflow`, `calligrastage`, `calligrasheets`. More information: <https://manned.org/calligrawords>.

name: cam
description: Frontend tool for `libcamera`. More information: <https://libcamera.org/docs.html>.

name: cancel

name: carbon-now
description: Create beautiful images of code. More information: <https://github.com/mixn/carbon-now-cli>.

name: carbonyl
description: View webpages on the terminal using a Chromium backend. See also: `browsh`. More information: <https://github.com/fathyb/carbonyl>.

name: cargo
description: Manage Rust projects and their module dependencies (crates). Some subcommands such as `build` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/cargo/>.

name: cargo-add
description: Add dependencies to a Rust project's `Cargo.toml` manifest. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-add.html>.

name: cargo-bench
description: Compile and execute benchmarks. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-bench.html>.

name: cargo-binstall
description: Install Rust binaries from CI artifacts. Falls back to `cargo install` (from source code) if there are no binaries available. More information: <https://github.com/cargo-bins/cargo-binstall>.

name: cargo-build
description: Compile a local package and all of its dependencies. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-build.html>.

name: cargo-check
description: Check a local package and all of its dependencies for errors. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-check.html>.

name: cargo-clean
description: Remove generated artifacts in the `target` directory. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-clean.html>.

name: cargo-clippy
description: A collection of lints to catch common mistakes and improve your Rust code. More information: <https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy>.

name: cargo-deb
description: Create Debian packages from Cargo projects. More information: <https://github.com/kornelski/cargo-deb>.

name: cargo-doc
description: Build the documentation of Rust packages. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-doc.html>.

name: cargo-fetch
description: Fetch dependencies of a package from the network. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-fetch.html>.

name: cargo-fix
description: Automatically fix lint warnings reported by `rustc`. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-fix.html>.

name: cargo-fmt
description: Run `rustfmt` on all source files in a Rust project. More information: <https://github.com/rust-lang/rustfmt>.

name: cargo-generate-lockfile
description: Generate the `Cargo.lock` file for the current package. Similar to `cargo update`, but has less options. If the lockfile already exists it will be rebuilt with latest version of every package. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/cargo/commands/cargo-generate-lockfile.html>.

name: cargo-help
description: Display help on `cargo` and its subcommands. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-help.html>.

name: cargo-info
description: Display information about a Rust package. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-info.html>.

name: cargo-init
description: Create a new Cargo package. Equivalent of `cargo new`, but specifying a directory is optional. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-init.html>.

name: cargo-install
description: Build and install a Rust binary. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-install.html>.

name: cargo-locate-project
description: Print the full path to the `Cargo.toml` manifest of a project. If the project is part of a workspace, the manifest of the project is shown, rather than that of the workspace. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-locate-project.html>.

name: cargo-login
description: Save an API token from the registry locally. The token is used to authenticate to a package registry. You can remove it using `cargo logout`. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-login.html>.

name: cargo-logout
description: Remove an API token from the registry locally. The token is used to authenticate to a package registry. You can add it back using `cargo login`. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-logout.html>.

name: cargo-metadata

name: cargo-msrv

name: cargo-new

name: cargo-owner

name: cargo-package
description: Assemble a local package into a distributable tarball (a `.crate` file). Similar to `cargo publish --dry-run`, but has more options. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-package.html>.

name: cargo-pkgid
description: Print the fully qualified package ID specifier for a package or dependency in the current workspace. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-pkgid.html>.

name: cargo-publish
description: Upload a package to a registry. Note: You have to add an authentication token using `cargo login` before publishing a package. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-publish.html>.

name: cargo-remove
description: Remove dependencies from a Rust project's `Cargo.toml` manifest. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-remove.html>.

name: cargo-report
description: Display various kinds of reports. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-report.html>.

name: cargo-run
description: Run the current Cargo package. Note: The working directory of the executed binary will be set to the current working directory. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-run.html>.

name: cargo-rustc
description: Compile a Rust package. Similar to `cargo build`, but you can pass extra options to the compiler. See `rustc --help` for all available options. More information: <https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-rustc.html>.

name: cargo-rustdoc

name: cargo-test

name: cargo-tree

name: cargo-uninstall

name: conda-deactivate

description: Log in or access credentials. More information: <https://github.com/google/go-containerregistry/blob/main/cmd/crane/doc/crane_auth.md>.

name: distrobox-create
description: Create a Distrobox container. The container created will be tightly integrated with the host, allowing sharing of the user's `$HOME` directory, external storage, external USB devices, graphical apps (X11/Wayland), and audio. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-create/>.

name: distrobox-enter
description: Enter a Distrobox container. Default command executed is your `$SHELL`, but you can specify different shells or entire commands to execute. If used inside a script, an application, or a service, you can use the `--headless` mode to disable the tty and interactivity. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-enter/>.

name: distrobox-export
description: Export app/service/binary from container to host OS. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-export/>.

name: distrobox-host-exec
description: Execute a command on the host from inside a Distrobox container. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-host-exec/>.

name: distrobox-list
description: List all Distrobox containers. Distrobox containers are listed separately from the rest of normal Podman or Docker containers. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-list/>.

name: distrobox-rm
description: Remove a Distrobox container. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-rm/>.

name: distrobox-stop
description: Stop a Distrobox container. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-stop/>.

name: distrobox-upgrade
description: Upgrade one or multiple Distrobox containers. See also: `distrobox`. More information: <https://distrobox.it/usage/distrobox-upgrade/>.

name: ditto
description: Copy files and directories. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/ditto.1.html>.

name: dive
description: Explore a Docker image, layer contents, and discover ways to shrink it. More information: <https://github.com/wagoodman/dive>.

name: django-admin
description: Django's utility for administrative tasks. More information: <https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/django-admin/>.

name: djxl
description: Decompress JPEG XL images. Accepted output extensions are PNG, APNG, JPEG, EXR, PGM, PPM, PNM, PFM, PAM, EXIF, XMP, and JUMBF. More information: <https://github.com/libjxl/libjxl/blob/main/doc/man/djxl.txt>.

name: dkms
description: A framework that allows for dynamic building of kernel modules. More information: <https://manned.org/dkms>.

name: dlv
description: Debugger for the Go programming language. More information: <https://github.com/go-delve/delve/blob/master/Documentation/usage/dlv.md>.

name: dm-tool
description: A tool to communicate with the display manager. More information: <https://manned.org/dm-tool>.

name: dmd
description: Official D compiler. More information: <https://dlang.org/dmd-windows.html>.

name: dmenu
description: Dynamic menu. Create a menu from a text input with each item on a new line. More information: <https://manned.org/dmenu>.

name: dmesg
description: Write the kernel messages to `stdout`. See also: `journalctl`. More information: <https://manned.org/dmesg>.

name: dmidecode
description: Display the DMI (alternatively known as SMBIOS) table contents in a human-readable format. Requires root privileges. More information: <https://manned.org/dmidecode>.

name: dmypy
description: Type check Python code, running `mypy` as a daemon for better speed. See also: `mypy` for more options to use with check and run. More information: <https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/stable/mypy_daemon.html>.

name: dnf
description: Package management utility for RHEL, Fedora, and CentOS (replaces yum). Some subcommands such as `group` and `config-manager` have their own usage documentation. For equivalent commands in other package managers, see <https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Pacman/Rosetta>. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html>.

name: dnf-builddep
description: Install dependencies to build a given package. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/builddep.html>.

name: dnf-changelog
description: View the changelogs for a given package. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/changelog.html>.

name: dnf-clean
description: Perform cleanup of temporary files kept for Red Hat-based repositories. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html#clean-command>.

name: dnf-config-manager
description: Manage DNF configuration options and repositories on Fedora-based systems. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/config_manager.html>.

name: dnf-deplist
description: This command is an alias of `dnf repoquery --deplist`.

name: dnf-download
description: Download RPM packages from the DNF repositories. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/download.html>.

name: dnf-group
description: Manage virtual collections of packages on Fedora-based systems. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html#group-command>.

name: dnf-install
description: Install packages on Red Hat-based distributions. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html#install-examples>.

name: dnf-module
description: Manage package modularity. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html#module-command>.

name: dnf-repoquery
description: Query packages for information. More information: <https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/command_ref.html#repoquery-command>.

name: dnf-reposync
description: Synchronize packages and metadata of a remote DNF repository to a local directory. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reposync.html>.

name: dnf-versionlock
description: Protect packages from updates to newer versions. Not default to `dnf` but supported via `dnf-plugins-core`. See also: `dnf`. More information: <https://dnf-plugins-core.readthedocs.io/en/latest/versionlock.html>.

name: dnf5
description: Package management utility for RHEL, Fedora, and CentOS (it replaces dnf, which in turn replaced yum). DNF5 is a C++ rewrite of the DNF package manager featuring improved performance and a smaller size. For equivalent commands in other package managers, see <https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Pacman/Rosetta>. More information: <https://dnf5.readthedocs.io/en/latest/commands/index.html>.

name: dnf5-group
description: This command is an alias of `dnf group`. Note: From Fedora 37 to 40 (inclusive), `dnf` runs DNF v4 while `dnf5` runs DNF v5.

name: dnsdomainname
description: Show the system's DNS domain name. Note: The tool uses `gethostname` to get the hostname of the system and then `getaddrinfo` to resolve it into a canonical name. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/inetutils/manual/inetutils.html#dnsdomainname-invocation>.

name: dnsmap
description: The dnsmap command scans a domain for common subdomains e.g. smtp.domain.org. More information: <https://github.com/resurrecting-open-source-projects/dnsmap>.

name: dnsmasq
description: Lightweight DNS, DHCP, TFTP, and PXE server. More information: <https://manned.org/dnsmasq>.

name: dnsrecon
description: DNS enumeration tool. More information: <https://manned.org/dnsrecon>.

name: dnstracer
description: The dnstracer command determines where a DNS gets its information from. More information: <https://manned.org/dnstracer>.

name: dnswalk
description: DNS debugger. "Walk" across zones and validate database consistency and best practices. More information: <https://manned.org/dnswalk>.

name: dnsx
description: A fast and multi-purpose DNS toolkit to run multiple DNS queries. Note: Input to `dnsx` needs to be passed through `stdin` (pipe `|`) in some cases. See also: `dig`, `dog`, `dnstracer`. More information: <https://docs.projectdiscovery.io/opensource/dnsx/usage>.

name: do
description: This shell keyword is used with `for`, `while`, `select`, and `until` to mark the start of a loop.

name: do-release-upgrade
description: The Ubuntu release upgrader. More information: <https://manned.org/do-release-upgrade>.

name: doas
description: Execute a command as another user. See also: `sudo`, `pkexec`, `run0`. More information: <https://man.openbsd.org/doas>.

name: dockdiver
description: A tool for interacting with Docker registries, including listing and dumping repositories. More information: <https://github.com/MachiavelliII/dockdiver#instructions>.

name: docker
description: Manage Docker containers and images. Some subcommands such as `container` and `image` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/>.

name: docker-build
description: Build an image from a Dockerfile. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/buildx/build/>.

name: docker-commit

name: docker-compose
description: Run and manage multi container Docker applications. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/>.

name: docker-compose-down

name: docker-compose-logs

name: docker-compose-up

name: docker-container

name: docker-container-commit

name: docker-container-cp
description: Copy files or directories between host and container filesystems. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/cp/>.

name: docker-container-diff
description: Inspect changes to files or directories on a container's filesystem. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/diff/>.

name: docker-container-exec
description: Execute a command on an already running Docker container. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/exec/>.

name: docker-container-logs

name: docker-container-remove

name: docker-container-rename
description: Rename a container. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/rename/>.

name: docker-container-rm
description: Remove containers. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/rm/>.

name: docker-container-run
description: Run a command in a new Docker container. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/run/>.

name: docker-container-start
description: Start stopped containers. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/start/>.

name: docker-container-stats
description: Display a live stream of resource usage statistics for containers. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/stats/>.

name: docker-container-top
description: Display the running processes of a container. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/top/>.

name: docker-container-update
description: Update configuration of Docker containers. This command is not supported for Windows containers. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/update/>.

name: docker-context
description: Switch between contexts to manage multiple Docker environments. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/context/>.

name: docker-cp
description: This command is an alias of `docker container cp`.

name: docker-diff

name: docker-exec
description: This command is an alias of `docker container exec`.

name: docker-image

description: Manage Docker images. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/image/ls/>.

name: docker-image-save

name: docker-image-tag

name: docker-load
description: This command is an alias of `docker image load`.

name: docker-login

name: docker-logs
description: This command is an alias of `docker container logs`.

name: docker-machine
description: Create and manage machines running Docker. More information: <https://github.com/docker-archive-public/docker.machine>.

name: docker-network
description: Create and manage Docker networks. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/network/>.

name: docker-node
description: Manage Docker Swarm nodes. More information: <https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/node/>.

name: docker-ps

name: docker-pull
description: This command is an alias of `docker image pull`.

name: docker-rename
description: This command is an alias of `docker container rename`.

name: docker-rm
description: This command is an alias of `docker container rm`.

description: This command is an alias of `docker image rm`.

name: docker-run
description: This command is an alias of `docker container run`.

name: docker-save
description: This command is an alias of `docker image save`.

name: docker-start
description: This command is an alias of `docker container start`.

description: This command is an alias of `docker container stats`.

name: docker-tag

name: docker-top
description: This command is an alias of `docker container top`.

description: This command is an alias of `docker container update`.

description: Manage DigitalOcean apps. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/apps/>.

name: doctl-databases
description: Manage your MySQL, Redis, PostgreSQL, and MongoDB database services. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/>.

name: doctl-databases-db
description: Manage databases that are served by a database cluster. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/db/>.

name: doctl-databases-firewalls
description: Manage firewalls for database clusters. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/firewalls/>.

name: doctl-databases-maintenance-window
description: Schedule, and check the schedule of, maintenance windows for your databases. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/maintenance-window/>.

name: doctl-databases-options
description: Enable the navigation of available options under each database engine. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/options/>.

name: doctl-databases-pool
description: Manage connection pools for your database cluster. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/pool/>.

name: doctl-databases-replica

name: doctl-databases-sql-mode
description: View and configure a MySQL database cluster's global SQL modes. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/databases/sql-mode/>.

name: doctl-databases-user

name: doctl-serverless
description: Manage serverless functions. More information: <https://docs.digitalocean.com/reference/doctl/reference/serverless/>.

name: doctum

name: dog

name: doggo

name: dokku
description: Docker powered mini-Heroku (PaaS). Easily deploy multiple apps to your server in different languages using a single `git-push` command. More information: <https://dokku.com/docs/deployment/application-deployment/>.

name: dolphin

name: dolt
description: An SQL database that you can fork, clone, branch, merge, push, and pull just like a Git repository. Some subcommands such as `commit` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli>.

name: dolt-add
description: Add the contents of a table to the list of Dolt staged tables. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-add>.

name: dolt-blame
description: Display commit information for each row of a Dolt table. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-blame>.

name: dolt-branch
description: Manage Dolt branches. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-branch>.

name: dolt-checkout
description: Checkout the work tree or tables to a branch or commit. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-checkout>.

name: dolt-clone
description: Clone a repository into a new directory. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-clone>.

name: dolt-commit
description: Commit staged changes to tables. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-commit>.

name: dolt-config
description: Read and write local (per repository) and global (per user) Dolt configuration variables. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-config>.

name: dolt-fetch
description: Download objects and refs from another repository. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-fetch>.

name: dolt-gc
description: Search the repository for data that are no longer referenced and no longer needed. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-gc>.

name: dolt-init
description: Create an empty Dolt data repository. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-init>.

name: dolt-merge
description: Join two or more development histories together. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-merge>.

name: dolt-sql
description: Run an SQL query. Multiple SQL statements must be separated by semicolons. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-sql>.

name: dolt-status

name: dolt-version
description: Display the current dolt CLI version. More information: <https://docs.dolthub.com/cli-reference/cli#dolt-version>.

name: done
description: This shell keyword is used with `for`, `while`, `select`, and `until` to mark the end of a loop.

name: doom

name: dropuser
description: Remove an existing PostgreSQL user (role). More information: <https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/app-dropuser.html>.

name: drupal
description: Generate boilerplate code, interact with and debug Drupal projects. Some subcommands such as `check` have their own usage documentation. `drupal` has been deprecated. Use `drush` instead. More information: <https://drupalize.me/topic/drupal-console>.

name: drush
description: Shell and scripting interface for Drupal. More information: <https://www.drush.org/latest/usage/>.

name: drutil

name: dtc

name: dub

name: duc

More information: <https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/zevv/duc/blob/master/doc/duc.1.html>.

name: duckdb
description: Client for DuckDB, an in-process analytical SQL engine. More information: <https://duckdb.org/docs/stable/clients/cli/arguments>.

name: duf
description: Disk Usage/Free Utility. More information: <https://github.com/muesli/duf#usage>.

description: A lock-free deduplication cloud backup tool. More information: <https://github.com/gilbertchen/duplicacy/wiki>.

description: Give an instant overview of which directories are using disk space. See also: `du`, `ncdu`. More information: <https://github.com/bootandy/dust#usage>.

name: duti

name: dutree
