description: Actively probes the Internet in order to analyze topology and performance. Includes some tools that start with `sc_`, for example `sc_warts2text` or `sc_ttlexp`. More information: <https://www.caida.org/catalog/software/scamper/>.

name: scan-build
description: Run a static analyzer over a codebase as part of performing a regular build. More information: <https://clang-analyzer.llvm.org/scan-build.html>.

name: scancel
description: Cancel a Slurm job. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/scancel.html>.

name: scanimage
description: Scan images with the Scanner Access Now Easy API. More information: <http://sane-project.org/man/scanimage.1.html>.

name: scb
description: This command is an alias of `Set-Clipboard`.

name: scc
description: Count lines of code. Written in Go. More information: <https://github.com/boyter/scc#usage>.

name: sccache
description: A fast C/C++/Rust compiler cache. Composed of a client and a server, both running on the machine. More information: <https://manned.org/sccache>.

name: sccmap
description: Extract strongly connected components of directed graphs. Graphviz filters: `acyclic`, `bcomps`, `comps`, `edgepaint`, `gvcolor`, `gvpack`, `mingle`, `nop`, `sccmap`, `tred`, & `unflatten`. More information: <https://www.graphviz.org/pdf/sccmap.1.pdf>.

name: scd
description: File manager focused on shell integration. More information: <https://github.com/cshuaimin/scd>.

name: scdoc
description: Generate `man` manual pages. More information: <https://git.sr.ht/~sircmpwn/scdoc/tree/master/item/scdoc.1.scd>.

name: scheme
description: MIT Scheme language interpreter and REPL (interactive shell). More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/mit-scheme/documentation/stable/mit-scheme-user.html#Command_002dLine-Options>.

name: schroot
description: Run a command or start an interactive shell with a different root directory. More customizable than `chroot`. More information: <https://wiki.debian.org/Schroot>.

name: scim
description: A curses based, vim-like spreadsheet calculator. Use `<h><j><k><l>` or `<ArrowKeys>` to navigate. More information: <https://github.com/andmarti1424/sc-im>.

name: scontrol
description: View information about and modify jobs. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/scontrol.html>.

name: scoop
description: The Scoop package manager. Some subcommands such as `bucket` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://github.com/ScoopInstaller/Scoop/wiki/Commands>.

name: scoop-bucket
description: Manage buckets: Git repositories containing files which describe how scoop installs applications. If Scoop doesn't know where the bucket is located its repository location must be specified. More information: <https://github.com/ScoopInstaller/Scoop/wiki/Buckets>.

name: scp
description: Secure copy. Copy files between hosts using Secure Copy Protocol over SSH. More information: <https://man.openbsd.org/scp>.

name: scrapy
description: Web-crawling framework. More information: <https://docs.scrapy.org/en/latest/topics/commands.html#using-the-scrapy-tool>.

name: scrcpy
description: Display and control your Android device on a desktop. More information: <https://github.com/Genymobile/scrcpy>.

name: screen
description: Hold a session open on a remote server. Manage multiple windows with a single SSH connection. See also: `tmux`, `zellij`. More information: <https://manned.org/screen>.

name: screencap
description: Take a screenshot of a mobile display. This command can only be used through `adb shell`. More information: <https://developer.android.com/tools/adb#screencap>.

name: screencapture
description: Utility to take screenshots and screen recordings. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/screencapture.1.html>.

name: screenfetch
description: Display system information. More information: <https://github.com/KittyKatt/screenFetch#running-screenfetch>.

name: screenkey
description: A screencast tool to display keys pressed. More information: <https://www.thregr.org/wavexx/software/screenkey/>.

name: script
description: Record all terminal output to a typescript file. More information: <https://manned.org/script>.

name: scriptlive
description: Execute a typescript created by the `script` command in real-time. See also: `script`. More information: <https://manned.org/scriptlive>.

name: scriptreplay
description: Replay a typescript created by the `script` command to `stdout`. More information: <https://manned.org/scriptreplay>.

name: scrontab
description: Manage Slurm crontab files. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/scrontab.html>.

name: scrot
description: Screen capture utility. More information: <https://manned.org/scrot>.

name: scrun
description: An OCI runtime proxy for Slurm that runs containers as jobs. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/scrun.html>.

name: scutil
description: Manage system configuration parameters. Require root privileges when setting configuration. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/scutil.8.html>.

name: sd
description: Intuitive find and replace. More information: <https://manned.org/sd>.

name: sdcv
description: StarDict, a dictionary client. Dictionaries are provided separately from the client. More information: <https://manned.org/sdcv>.

name: sdef
description: Get or generate a scripting definitions (`sdef`) file from a scriptable application. More information: <https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/Cocoa/Conceptual/ScriptableCocoaApplications/SApps_creating_sdef/SAppsCreateSdef.html>.

name: sdelete
description: Securely delete file/directory from disk, or clean the free space on a volume/physical disk. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/sysinternals/downloads/sdelete>.

name: sdelete64
description: This command is the 64 bit version of `sdelete`.

name: sdiag
description: Show information about the execution of `slurmctld`. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/sdiag.html>.

name: sdiff
description: Compare the differences between and optionally merge 2 files. More information: <https://manned.org/sdiff>.

name: sdk
description: Manage parallel versions of multiple Software Development Kits. Supports Java, Groovy, Scala, Kotlin, Gradle, Maven, Vert.x and many others. More information: <https://sdkman.io/usage/>.

name: sdkmanager
description: Install packages for the Android SDK. More information: <https://developer.android.com/tools/sdkmanager>.

name: sealert
description: Analyze and explain SELinux AVC denial messages. Part of the `setroubleshoot-server` package. See also: `audit2why`, `ausearch`, `audit2allow`. More information: <https://manned.org/sealert>.

name: searchsploit
description: Search Exploit Database for exploits, shellcodes and/or papers. If known version numbers are used as search terms, exploits for both the exact version and others whose version range covers the one specified are shown. More information: <https://www.exploit-db.com/searchsploit>.

name: secd
description: Controls access to and modification of keychain items. It should not be invoked manually. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/secd.8.html>.

name: secon
description: Get the SELinux security context of a file, pid, current execution context, or a context specification. See also: `semanage`, `runcon`, `chcon`. More information: <https://manned.org/secon>.

name: secret-tool
description: Store and retrieve passwords, part of the `libsecret` package. Communicates with Freedesktop secret service implementations such as `gnome-keyring`. More information: <https://gnome.pages.gitlab.gnome.org/libsecret/>.

name: secrethub
description: Keep secrets out of configuration files. More information: <https://github.com/secrethub/secrethub-cli>.

name: secretsdump.py
description: Dump NTLM hashes, plaintext passwords, and domain credentials from remote Windows systems. Part of the Impacket suite. More information: <https://github.com/fortra/impacket>.

name: security
description: Administer keychains, keys, certificates, and the Security framework. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/security.1.html>.

name: security-checker
description: Check if a PHP application uses dependencies with known security vulnerabilities. More information: <https://github.com/sensiolabs/security-checker>.

name: securityd
description: This manages security contexts and cryptographic operations. Works with secd for keychain access. It should not be invoked manually. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/securityd.1.html>.

name: sed
description: Edit text in a scriptable manner. See also: `awk`, `ed`. More information: <https://man.freebsd.org/cgi/man.cgi?sed>.

name: see
description: Alias to `run-mailcap`'s view. An alias to a `run-mailcap`'s action print. More information: <https://manned.org/see>.

name: select
description: Bash builtin construct for creating menus. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#index-select>.

name: select-string
description: Finds text in strings and files in PowerShell. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. You can use `Select-String` similar to `grep` in UNIX or `findstr.exe` in Windows. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/select-string>.

name: selinuxenabled
description: Check whether SELinux is enabled. Returns exit code 0 if SELinux is enabled, and 1 if it is not. See also: `getenforce`, `setenforce`, `sestatus`. More information: <https://manned.org/selinuxenabled>.

name: semanage
description: SELinux persistent policy management tool. Some subcommands such as `boolean`, `fcontext`, `port`, etc. have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage>.

name: semanage-boolean
description: Manage persistent SELinux boolean settings. See also: `semanage` for managing SELinux policies, `getsebool` for checking boolean values, and `setsebool` for applying non-persistent boolean settings. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-boolean>.

name: semanage-fcontext
description: Manage persistent SELinux security context rules on files/directories. See also: `semanage`, `matchpathcon`, `secon`, `chcon`, `restorecon`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-fcontext>.

name: semanage-interface
description: Manage SELinux network interface type definitions. See also: `semanage`, `semanage-port`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-interface>.

name: semanage-login
description: Manage SELinux login mappings between Linux users and SELinux users. See also: `semanage`, `semanage-user`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-login>.

name: semanage-permissive
description: Manage persistent SELinux permissive domains. Note that this effectively makes the process unconfined. For long-term use, it is recommended to configure SELiunx properly. See also: `semanage`, `getenforce`, `setenforce`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-permissive>.

name: semanage-port
description: Manage persistent SELinux port definitions. See also: `semanage`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-port>.

name: semanage-user
description: Manage SELinux user mappings. See also: `semanage`, `semanage-login`. More information: <https://manned.org/semanage-user>.

name: semodule
description: Manage SELinux policy modules. See also: `audit2allow`, `semanage`. More information: <https://manned.org/semodule>.

name: semver
description: Semantic version string parser. More information: <https://github.com/npm/node-semver>.

name: sendmail
description: Send email. More information: <https://manned.org/sendmail>.

name: sensible-browser
description: Open the default browser. More information: <https://manned.org/sensible-browser>.

name: sensible-editor
description: Open the default editor. More information: <https://manned.org/sensible-editor>.

name: sensors
description: Report sensors information. More information: <https://manned.org/sensors>.

name: seq
description: Output a sequence of numbers to `stdout`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/seq-invocation.html>.

name: sequelize
description: Promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite, and Microsoft SQL Server. More information: <https://sequelize.org/docs/v7/cli/>.

name: sequin
description: Make ANSI escape sequences human-readable. Useful for debugging, learning, or inspecting terminal output. More information: <https://github.com/charmbracelet/sequin>.

name: serialver
description: Returns the serialVersionUID of classes. It does not set a security manager by default. More information: <https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/specs/man/serialver.html>.

name: serve
description: Static file serving and directory listing. More information: <https://github.com/vercel/serve>.

name: serverless
description: Toolkit for deploying and operating serverless architectures on AWS, Google Cloud, Azure, and IBM OpenWhisk. Commands can be run either using the `serverless` command or its alias, `sls`. More information: <https://www.serverless.com/framework/docs/providers/aws/cli-reference>.

name: service
description: Manage services by running init scripts. The full script path should be omitted (`/etc/init.d/` is assumed). More information: <https://manned.org/service>.

name: sesearch
description: Search SELinux policy rules. Part of the `setools` package. See also: `semodule`. More information: <https://manned.org/sesearch>.

name: sestatus
description: Print the current SELinux status. More information: <https://manned.org/sestatus>.

name: set
description: Toggle shell options or set the values of positional parameters. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#The-Set-Builtin>.

name: set-acl
description: Changes the security descriptor of a specified item, such as a file or a registry key. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.security/set-acl>.

name: set-alias
description: A PowerShell command to set or modify alias. Note: `sal` can be used as an alias for `Set-Alias`. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/set-alias>.

name: set-clipboard
description: PowerShell command to set content to clipboard. Note: `scb` can be used as an alias for `Set-Clipboard`. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/set-clipboard>.

name: set-date
description: Changes the system time on the computer to a time that you specify. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/set-date>.

name: set-location
description: Display the current working directory or move to a different directory. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/set-location>.

name: set-nodeinstalllocation
description: Set the default Node.js installation directory for `ps-nvm`. This command is part of `ps-nvm` and can only be run under PowerShell. More information: <https://github.com/aaronpowell/ps-nvm>.

name: set-nodeversion
description: Set the default Node.js version for `ps-nvm`. Part of `ps-nvm` and can only be run under PowerShell. More information: <https://github.com/aaronpowell/ps-nvm>.

name: set-service
description: Starts, stops, and suspends a service, and changes its properties. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.management/set-service>.

name: set-volume
description: Sets or changes the file system label of an existing volume. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/storage/set-volume>.

name: setarch
description: Change the reported architecture for a program's execution, primarily used to modify how programs behave based on system architecture. Useful for compatibility testing or running legacy applications. More information: <https://manned.org/setarch>.

name: setcap
description: Set capabilities of specified file. See also: `getcap`. More information: <https://manned.org/setcap>.

name: setenforce
description: Toggle SELinux between enforcing and permissive modes. To enable or disable SELinux, edit `/etc/selinux/config` instead. See also: `getenforce`, `semanage-permissive`. More information: <https://manned.org/setenforce>.

name: setfacl
description: Set file access control lists (ACL). More information: <https://manned.org/setfacl>.

name: setfattr
description: Set extended file attributes. More information: <https://manned.org/setfattr>.

name: setfile
description: Set file attributes on files in an HFS+ directory. More information: <https://ss64.com/mac/setfile.html>.

name: setfiles
description: Set SELinux file security contexts based on policy rules. Similar to `restorecon` but reads contexts from a file_contexts file. See also: `restorecon`, `semanage-fcontext`, `fixfiles`. More information: <https://manned.org/setfiles>.

name: setfont
description: Set the terminal font for TTYs. More information: <https://manned.org/setfont>.

name: setopt
description: Set Z shell (`zsh`) options. Note: Zsh options are case-insensitive and underscores are ignored. See also: `unsetopt` to unset options. More information: <https://zsh.sourceforge.io/Doc/Release/Options.html>.

name: setsebool
description: Set SELinux boolean value. See also: `semanage-boolean`, `getsebool`. More information: <https://manned.org/setsebool>.

name: setserial
description: Read and modify serial port information. More information: <https://manned.org/setserial>.

name: setsid
description: Run a program in a new session if the calling process is not a process group leader. The created session is by default not controlled by the current terminal. More information: <https://manned.org/setsid>.

name: settings
description: Get information about the Android OS. More information: <https://web.archive.org/web/20240525010124/https://adbinstaller.com/commands/adb-shell-settings-5b670d5ee7958178a2955536>.

name: setx
description: Set persistent environment variables. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/setx>.

name: setxkbmap
description: Set the keyboard using the X Keyboard Extension. More information: <https://manned.org/setxkbmap>.

name: sf
description: A powerful command-line interface that simplifies development and build automation when working with your Salesforce org. More information: <https://developer.salesforce.com/tools/salesforcecli>.

name: sfc
description: Scans the integrity of Windows system files. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/sfc>.

name: sfdisk
description: Display or manipulate a disk partition table. More information: <https://manned.org/sfdisk>.

name: sfdk
description: Frontend of the Sailfish SDK. Some subcommands such as `init`, `build-init`, `device` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/10-general/doc/module.adoc>.

name: sfdk-apply
description: Apply patches from RPM SPEC file. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.apply.adoc>.

name: sfdk-build-init
description: Initialize build directory. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.build-init.adoc>.

name: sfdk-build-requires
description: Update build time dependencies. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.build-requires.adoc>.

name: sfdk-build-shell
description: Execute custom steps in build engine. See also: `sfdk config` for configuring the build target and `sfdk build-init` for initializing build tree. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.build-shell.adoc>.

name: sfdk-check
description: Perform quality checks. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.cmake.adoc>.

name: sfdk-cmake
description: Execute cmake build step. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.cmake.adoc>.

name: sfdk-compiledb
description: Generate compilation database. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/70-ide-compiledb/doc/command.compiledb.adoc>.

name: sfdk-config
description: Configure sfdk. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/10-general/doc/command.config.adoc>.

name: sfdk-deploy
description: Deploy build results to a device. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/50-testing-mb2/doc/command.deploy.adoc>.

name: sfdk-device
description: Maintain and control registered devices. More information: <https://docs.sailfishos.org/Develop/Apps/Tutorials/Building_packages_-_advanced_techniques/#running-the-sample-application-in-the-emulator>.

name: sfdk-emulator
description: Maintain and control emulators. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/40-testing-maintain/doc/command.emulator.adoc>.

name: sfdk-emulator-device-model-list
description: This command has been moved to `sfdk emulator device-model-show`.

name: sfdk-emulator-device-model-show
description: Show emulated device model's properties. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/40-testing-maintain/doc/command.emulator.adoc>.

name: sfdk-emulator-install
description: Install emulators. More information: <https://docs.sailfishos.org/Tools/Sailfish_SDK/Early_Access/#early-access-build-targets-and-emulator>.

name: sfdk-emulator-remove
description: This command has been moved to `sfdk emulator install`.

name: sfdk-engine
description: Maintain and control the build engine. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/30-building-maintain/doc/command.engine.adoc>.

name: sfdk-init
description: Initialize a new project. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/15-building-init/doc/command.init.adoc>.

name: sfdk-maintain
description: Launch the interactive SDK Maintenance tool. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/10-general/doc/command.maintain.adoc>.

name: sfdk-make
description: Execute make build step. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.make.adoc>.

name: sfdk-make-install
description: Execute make-install build step. More information: <https://docs.sailfishos.org/Develop/Apps/Tutorials/Building_packages_-_advanced_techniques/#building-the-sample-application>.

name: sfdk-package
description: Execute package creation build step. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.package.adoc>.

name: sfdk-prepare
description: Execute preparation build step. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.prepare.adoc>.

name: sfdk-qmake
description: Execute qmake build step. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/20-building-mb2/doc/command.qmake.adoc>.

name: sfdk-qmltypes
description: Generate qmltypes files. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/80-ide-qmltypes/doc/command.qmltypes.adoc>.

name: sfdk-scrape
description: Convert source code modifications to patches. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/65-maintaining-mb2/doc/command.scrape.adoc>.

name: sfdk-undeploy
description: Undeploy build results from a device. More information: <https://github.com/sailfishos/sailfish-qtcreator/blob/master/share/qtcreator/sfdk/modules/50-testing-mb2/doc/command.undeploy.adoc>.

name: sfdp
description: Render an image of a `scaled force-directed` network graph from a `graphviz` file. Layouts: `dot`, `neato`, `twopi`, `circo`, `fdp`, `sfdp`, `osage` & `patchwork`. More information: <https://graphviz.org/doc/info/command.html>.

name: sfill
description: Securely overwrite the free space and inodes of the partition where the specified directory resides. More information: <https://manned.org/sfill>.

name: sftp
description: Secure File Transfer Program. Interactive program to copy files between hosts over SSH. For non-interactive file transfers, see `scp` or `rsync`. More information: <https://manned.org/sftp>.

name: sg
description: Ast-grep is a tool for code structural search, lint, and rewriting. More information: <https://ast-grep.github.io/guide/introduction.html>.

name: sg_raw
description: Send arbitrary SCSI command to a connected device. More information: <https://manned.org/sg_raw>.

name: sgdisk
description: Manage GUID Partition Tables (GPT). Part of the GPT fdisk suite; designed for scripting and automation. More information: <https://manned.org/sgdisk>.

name: sgitopnm
description: Convert an SGI file to a PNM file. More information: <https://netpbm.sourceforge.net/doc/sgitopnm.html>.

name: sgpt
description: Productivity tool powered by OpenAI's GPT models. More information: <https://github.com/TheR1D/shell_gpt#readme>.

name: sh
description: Bourne shell, the standard command language interpreter. See also: `!` and `^` for history expansion. More information: <https://manned.org/sh>.

name: sh5util
description: Merge HDF5 files produced by the `sacct_gather_profile` plugin. More information: <https://slurm.schedmd.com/sh5util.html>.

name: sha1sum
description: Calculate SHA1 cryptographic checksums. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/sha1sum-invocation.html>.

name: sha224sum
description: Calculate SHA224 cryptographic checksums. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/sha2-utilities.html>.

name: sha256sum
description: Calculate SHA256 cryptographic checksums. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/sha2-utilities.html>.

name: sha384sum
description: Calculate SHA384 cryptographic checksums. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/sha2-utilities.html>.

name: sha512sum

name: systemctl-add-requires

name: systemctl-bind

name: systemctl-cancel

description: Show the full contents of unit files as systemd sees them. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#cat%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-condrestart
description: This command is an alias of `systemctl try-restart`.

name: systemctl-condstop
description: This command is an alias of `systemctl stop`.

name: systemctl-default
description: Enter system default mode. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#default>.

name: systemctl-disable
description: Disable systemd services. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#disable%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-edit
description: Edit systemd unit files. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#edit%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-emergency
description: Enter emergency mode `emergency.target`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#emergency>.

name: systemctl-enable
description: Enable systemd services. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#enable%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-exit
description: Ask the service manager to quit. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#exit%20EXIT_CODE>.

description: This command is an alias of `systemctl try-reload-or-restart`.

name: systemctl-help

description: Import environment variables from the shell into systemd's environment. See also: `systemctl show-environment`, `systemctl unset-environment`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemctl.html#import-environment%20VARIABLE%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-is-active
description: Check if one or more systemd units are active. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#is-active%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-is-enabled
description: Check whether unit files are enabled. See also: `systemctl enable`, `systemctl disable`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#is-enabled%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-kill

name: systemctl-list-dependencies

name: systemctl-list-jobs

name: systemctl-list-unit-files
description: List installed unit files and their enablement states. See also: `systemctl list-units` for listing units currently loaded in memory. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#list-unit-files%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-list-units
description: List units that systemd currently has in memory. See also: `systemctl list-unit-files` for listing installed unit files. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#list-units%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-log-level
description: Get or set the log level of the systemd manager. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#log-level%20[LEVEL]>.

name: systemctl-log-target
description: Get or set the log target for the systemd manager. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#log-target%20[TARGET]>.

name: systemctl-mask
description: Link units to `/dev/null` so that they can be even started. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#mask%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-mount-image
description: Mount an image file into a unit's mount namespace. Only supported for the units that run within a mountspace ie, with `RootImage=`, `PrivateMounts=`, etc. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemctl.html#mount-image%20UNIT%20IMAGE%20%5BPATH%20%5BPARTITION_NAME:MOUNT_OPTIONS%5D%5D>.

name: systemctl-poweroff
description: Power off the system. See also: `poweroff`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#poweroff>.

name: systemctl-preset
description: Reset the enablement state of unit files to the defaults specified in preset policy files. See also: `systemctl preset-all`, `systemctl list-unit-files`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#preset%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-preset-all
description: Reset the enablement state of all installed units to the defaults specified in preset policy files. See also: `systemctl preset`, `systemctl list-unit-files`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#preset-all>.

name: systemctl-reboot
description: Reboot the system. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#reboot>.

name: systemctl-reenable
description: Re-enable one or more units. Used when targets of a service change. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#reenable%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-reload
description: Reload a service's configuration without restarting it. This reloads the service itself (like Apache or Nginx configs), not the systemd unit file. To reload unit files, use `systemctl daemon-reload`.

name: systemctl-reload-or-restart
description: Reload `systemd` unit(s) otherwise restart them. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#reload-or-restart%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-reload-or-try-restart
description: This command is an alias of `systemctl try-reload-or-restart`.

name: systemctl-rescue
description: Enter rescue mode. See also: `systemctl emergency`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#rescue>.

name: systemctl-reset-failed
description: Reset the "failed" state of one or more units. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#reset-failed%20%5BPATTERN%E2%80%A6%5D>.

name: systemctl-restart
description: Stop and then start one or more systemd units. Can be used in place of `systemctl start` on a stopped unit, but `start` is safer so that a running unit isn't accidentally restarted. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#restart%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-revert
description: Revert unit files to their vendor versions. Undoes the effects of `edit`, `enable`, `disable`, `set-property`, and `mask`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#revert%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-service-log-level
description: Get or set the runtime log level of a service via D-Bus. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#service-log-level%20SERVICE%20%5BLEVEL%5D>.

name: systemctl-service-log-target
description: Get or set the log target for a service. Only works for D-Bus integrated services. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#service-log-target%20SERVICE%20[TARGET]>.

name: systemctl-service-watchdogs
description: Get or set the global state of service runtime watchdogs. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#service-watchdogs%20[yes|no]>.

name: systemctl-set-default
description: Symlink the `default.target` alias to the given target unit. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#set-default%20TARGET>.

name: systemctl-set-environment
description: Set one or more service manager environment variables. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#set-environment%20VARIABLE=VALUE%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-set-property
description: Set the specified unit properties at runtime. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#set-property%20UNIT%20PROPERTY=VALUE%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-show
description: Show properties of units or systemd itself. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#show%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6%7CJOB%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-show-environment
description: Display systemd environment blocks. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#show-environment>.

name: systemctl-soft-reboot
description: Shut down and reboot userspace, leaving the kernel running. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#soft-reboot>.

name: systemctl-start
description: Start systemd units. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#start%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-status
description: Display the status of systemd units. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#status%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6%7CPID%E2%80%A6%5D>.

name: systemctl-stop
description: Stop systemd units. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#stop%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-suspend
description: Suspend the system. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#suspend>.

name: systemctl-suspend-then-hibernate
description: Suspend the system, then automatically hibernate after a period of inactivity. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#suspend-then-hibernate>.

name: systemctl-switch-root
description: Switch to a new root filesystem and execute a new system manager. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#switch-root%20ROOT%20INIT>.

name: systemctl-thaw
description: Thaw (resume) one or more frozen units. Units can be frozen with `systemctl freeze`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#thaw%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-try-reload-or-restart
description: Reload one or more units if they support it; otherwise restart them. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#try-reload-or-restart%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-try-restart
description: Restart one or more units only if they are currently running. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#try-restart%20PATTERN%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-unmask
description: Unmask units to make them startable again. This undoes the effect of `systemctl mask`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#unmask%20UNIT%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-unset-environment
description: Unset one or more service manager environment variables. This undoes the effect of `systemctl set-environment`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#unset-environment%20VARIABLE%E2%80%A6>.

name: systemctl-whoami
description: Show units that processes belong to. If no PID is specified, shows the unit the `systemctl` command itself is invoked in. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemctl.html#whoami%20%5BPID%E2%80%A6%5D>.

name: systemd-ac-power
description: Report whether the computer is connected to an external power source. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-ac-power.html>.

name: systemd-analyze
description: Analyze and debug system manager. Show timing details about the boot process of units (services, mount points, devices, sockets). More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-analyze.html>.

name: systemd-ask-password
description: Query the user for a system password. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-ask-password.html>.

name: systemd-cat
description: Connect a pipeline or program's output streams with the systemd journal. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-cat.html>.

name: systemd-cgls
description: Show the contents of the selected Linux control group hierarchy in a tree. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-cgls.html>.

name: systemd-cgtop
description: Show the top control groups of the local Linux control group hierarchy, ordered by their CPU, memory, or disk I/O load. See also: `top`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-cgtop.html>.

name: systemd-confext
description: This command is an alias of `systemd-sysext`. It follows the same principle as `systemd-sysext`, but instead of working on `/usr` and `/opt`, `confext` will extend only `/etc`.

name: systemd-creds
description: List, show, encrypt, and decrypt service credentials. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-creds.html>.

name: systemd-cryptenroll
description: Interactively enroll or remove methods used to unlock LUKS2-encrypted devices. Uses a password to unlock the device unless otherwise specified. In order to allow a partition to be unlocked during system boot, update the `/etc/crypttab` file or the initramfs. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-cryptenroll.html>.

name: systemd-cryptsetup
description: Create or remove decrypted mappings of encrypted volumes. Equivalent of `cryptsetup open` and `cryptsetup close`. Arguments to this command are written exactly like a line in `/etc/crypttab`. It's used by systemd to unlock devices on boot. See also: `cryptsetup`. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-cryptsetup.html>.

name: systemd-delta
description: Find overridden systemd-related configuration files. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-delta.html>.

name: systemd-detect-virt
description: Detect execution in a virtualized environment. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-detect-virt.html>.

name: systemd-dissect
description: Introspect and interact with file system OS disk images, specifically Discoverable Disk Images (DDIs). More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-dissect.html>.

name: systemd-escape
description: Escape strings for usage in systemd unit names. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-escape.html>.

name: systemd-firstboot
description: Initialize basic system settings on or before the first boot-up of a system. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-firstboot.html>.

name: systemd-hwdb
description: Hardware database management tool. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-hwdb.html>.

name: systemd-id128
description: Generate and print sd-128 identifiers. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-id128.html>.

name: systemd-inhibit
description: Prohibit the system from entering certain power states. Inhibitor locks may be used to block or delay system sleep and shutdown requests as well as automatic idle handling. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-inhibit.html>.

name: systemd-machine-id-setup
description: Initialize the machine ID stored in `/etc/machine-id` at install time with a provisioned or randomly generated ID. Note: Always use `sudo` to execute these commands as they require elevated privileges. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-machine-id-setup.html>.

name: systemd-mount
description: Establish and destroy transient mount or auto-mount points. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-mount.html>.

name: systemd-notify
description: Notify the service manager about start-up completion and other daemon status changes. This command is useless outside systemd service scripts. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-notify.html>.

name: systemd-nspawn
description: Spawn a command or OS in a lightweight container. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-nspawn.html>.

name: systemd-path
description: List and query system and user paths. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-path.html>.

name: systemd-repart
description: Automatically grow and add partitions. Grows and adds partitions based on the configuration files described in repart.d. Does not automatically resize file system on partition. See systemd-growfs to extend file system. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-repart.html>.

name: systemd-resolve
description: Resolve domain names, IPV4 and IPv6 addresses, DNS resource records, and services. Note: This tool has been renamed to `resolvectl` in new versions of `systemd`. More information: <https://manned.org/systemd-resolve>.

name: systemd-run
description: Run programs in transient scope units, service units, or path-, socket-, or timer-triggered service units. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-run.html>.

name: systemd-socket-activate
description: Socket activation for systemd services. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-socket-activate.html>.

name: systemd-stdio-bridge
description: Implement a proxy between `stdin`/`stdout` and a D-Bus. Note: It expects to receive an open connection via `stdin`/`stdout` when started, and will create a new connection to the specified bus. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-stdio-bridge.html>.

name: systemd-sysext
description: Activate or deactivate system extension images. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-sysext.html>.

name: systemd-sysusers
description: Create system users and groups. If the config file is not specified, files in the `sysusers.d` directories are used. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-sysusers.html>.

name: systemd-tmpfiles
description: Create, delete, and clean up volatile and temporary files and directories. This command is automatically invoked on boot by systemd services and running it manually is usually not needed. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-tmpfiles.html>.

name: systemd-tty-ask-password-agent
description: List or process pending systemd password requests. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/systemd-tty-ask-password-agent.html>.

name: systemd-umount
description: This command is an alias of `systemd-mount --umount`.

name: systeminfo
description: Display operating system configuration for a local or remote machine. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/systeminfo>.

name: systemsettings
description: KDE central settings program. More information: <https://manned.org/systemsettings>.

name: systemsetup
description: Configure System Preferences machine settings. More information: <https://support.apple.com/guide/remote-desktop/about-systemsetup-apd95406b8d/mac>.

name: systemsoundserverd
description: Core Audio related daemon. It should not be invoked manually.

name: systool
description: View system device information by bus, and classes. This command is part of the `sysfs` package. More information: <https://manned.org/systool>.

name: tabula
description: Extract tables from PDF files. More information: <https://github.com/tabulapdf/tabula-java#commandline-usage-examples>.

name: tac
description: Display and concatenate files with lines in reversed order. See also: `cat`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tac-invocation.html>.

name: tag
description: Edit tags on Mac OS X files (10.9 Mavericks and above). More information: <https://github.com/jdberry/tag#usage>.

name: tail
description: Display the last part of a file. See also: `head`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tail-invocation.html>.

name: tailf
description: This command has been superseded by `tail -f`. More information: <https://manned.org/tailf>.

name: tailscale
description: A private WireGuard network service. Some subcommands such as `up` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1080/cli>.

name: tailscale-file
description: Send files across connected devices on a Tailscale network. It currently does not support sending files to devices owned by other users even on the same Tailscale network. More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1106/taildrop>.

name: tailscale-funnel
description: Share a local server on the internet using Tailscale. More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1311/tailscale-funnel>.

name: tailscale-set
description: Change the specified preferences. These options can also be changed during the initial setup. This command can set all options documented in the page for `tailscale up`. More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1080/cli#set>.

name: tailscale-ssh
description: SSH to a Tailscale machine (Linux Only). More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1193/tailscale-ssh>.

name: tailscale-up
description: Connect the client to the Tailscale network. Note: Run `sudo tailscale set --operator $USER` to allow the current user to run these commands. All options described here can be changed later using `tailscale set --option argument`. Use `--option=false` to disable options that don't require arguments. More information: <https://tailscale.com/kb/1080/cli/#up>.

name: takeout
description: A Docker-based development-only dependency manager. More information: <https://github.com/tighten/takeout>.

name: takeown
description: Take ownership of a file or directory. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/takeown>.

name: talk
description: A visual communication program which copies lines from your terminal to that of another user. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/inetutils/manual/inetutils.html#talk-invocation>.

name: talosctl
description: Interact with Talos Linux, a minimal and immutable Kubernetes distribution. See also: `kubectl`. More information: <https://docs.siderolabs.com/talos/v1.11/reference/cli>.

name: tar
description: Archiving utility. Often combined with a compression method, such as `gzip` or `bzip2`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/tar/manual/tar.html>.

name: tarsnap
description: Manipulate remote Tarsnap encrypted backups. Note: You don't need to specify the key file and the cache directory if you configure them in `/usr/local/etc/tarsnap.conf` or `~/.tarsnaprc`. See also: `tarsnap-keygen`. More information: <https://www.tarsnap.com/man-tarsnap.1.html>.

name: tarsnap-keygen
description: Generate a key file for use with Tarsnap, an online backup service. More information: <https://www.tarsnap.com/man-tarsnap-keygen.1.html>.

name: tart
description: Build, run, and manage macOS and Linux virtual machines (VMs) on Apple Silicon. More information: <https://github.com/cirruslabs/tart>.

name: task
description: To-do list manager. More information: <https://taskwarrior.org/docs/>.

name: taskkill
description: Terminate a process by its process ID or name. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/taskkill>.

name: tasklist
description: Display a list of currently running processes on a local or remote machine. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/tasklist>.

name: taskset
description: Get or set a process' CPU affinity or start a new process with a defined CPU affinity. More information: <https://manned.org/taskset>.

name: tb
description: Manage tasks and notes across multiple boards. More information: <https://github.com/klaudiosinani/taskbook#usage>.

name: tbl
description: Table preprocessor for the groff (GNU Troff) document formatting system. See also: `groff`, `troff`. More information: <https://manned.org/tbl>.

name: tc
description: Show/manipulate traffic control settings. More information: <https://manned.org/tc>.

name: tcc
description: A tiny C compiler that can run C source files as scripts and otherwise has command-line options similar to `gcc`. More information: <https://bellard.org/tcc/tcc-doc.html>.

name: tcpdump
description: Dump traffic on a network. More information: <https://www.tcpdump.org/manpages/tcpdump.1.html>.

name: tcpflow
description: Capture TCP traffic for debugging and analysis. More information: <https://manned.org/tcpflow>.

name: tcpick
description: Packet sniffing and network traffic analysis tool. It can capture and display TCP connections and data. It can also monitor network traffic on a interface, host, or port. More information: <https://manned.org/tcpick>.

name: tcpkill
description: Kill specified in-progress TCP connections. More information: <https://manned.org/tcpkill>.

name: tcpreplay
description: Replay network traffic stored in a `pcap` file. More information: <https://tcpreplay.appneta.com/wiki/tcpreplay-man.html>.

name: tcptraceroute
description: A traceroute implementation using TCP packets. More information: <https://manned.org/tcptraceroute>.

name: tcsh
description: C shell with file name completion and command-line editing. See also: `csh`. More information: <https://manned.org/tcsh>.

name: tdf
description: A tui PDF viewer. More information: <https://github.com/itsjunetime/tdf>.

name: tea
description: Interact with Gitea servers. More information: <https://gitea.com/gitea/tea>.

name: tectonic
description: A modern, self-contained TeX/LaTeX engine. More information: <https://tectonic-typesetting.github.io/book/latest/>.

name: tee
description: Read from `stdin` and write to `stdout` and files (or commands). More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tee-invocation.html>.

name: tee-object
description: Saves command output in a file or variable and also sends it down the pipeline. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/tee-object>.

name: telegram-desktop
description: Instant messenger with open source clients, chats, and stickers. More information: <https://manned.org/telegram-desktop>.

name: telinit
description: Change SysV runlevel. Since the concept SysV runlevels is obsolete the runlevel requests will be transparently translated into systemd unit activation requests. More information: <https://manned.org/telinit>.

name: telnet
description: Connect to a specified port of a host using the telnet protocol. More information: <https://manned.org/telnet>.

name: termdown
description: Countdown timer and stopwatch. More information: <https://github.com/trehn/termdown>.

name: terminal-notifier
description: Send macOS User Notifications. More information: <https://github.com/julienXX/terminal-notifier>.

name: terminalizer
description: Record the terminal, generate animated GIFs and a web player, and optionally upload to <https://terminalizer.com>. See also: `asciinema`. More information: <https://www.terminalizer.com/docs#getting-started>.

name: terminator
description: Arrange multiple GNOME terminals in one window. More information: <https://gnome-terminator.readthedocs.io/en/latest/advancedusage.html>.

name: termshark
description: Terminal UI for `tshark`, but looks more like `wireshark`. More information: <https://github.com/gcla/termshark/blob/master/docs/UserGuide.md>.

name: termusic
description: A terminal music player written in Rust that uses vim-like key bindings. See also: `cmus`, `ncmpcpp`, `audacious`. More information: <https://github.com/tramhao/termusic>.

name: terraform
description: Create and deploy infrastructure as code to cloud providers. More information: <https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands>.

name: terraform-fmt
description: Format configuration according to Terraform language style conventions. More information: <https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/fmt>.

name: terraform-output
description: Export structured data about your Terraform resources. More information: <https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/output>.

name: terraform-plan
description: Generate and show Terraform execution plans. More information: <https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan>.

name: terragrunt
description: Keep your Terraform CLI arguments DRY. More information: <https://terragrunt.gruntwork.io/docs/reference/cli/>.

name: terraria
description: Create and start a headless Terraria server. More information: <https://terraria.wiki.gg/wiki/Server>.

name: tesseract
description: OCR (Optical Character Recognition) engine. More information: <https://github.com/tesseract-ocr/tesseract/blob/main/doc/tesseract.1.asc>.

name: test
description: Check file types and compare values. Returns 0 if the condition evaluates to true, 1 if it evaluates to false. See also: `[`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/test-invocation.html>.

name: test-json
description: Test whether a string is a valid JSON document. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/test-json>.

name: test-netconnection
description: Display diagnostic information for a connection. Note: This command can only be used through PowerShell. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/nettcpip/test-netconnection>.

name: testssl
description: Check SSL/TLS protocols and ciphers supported by a server. More information: <https://testssl.sh/doc/testssl.1.html>.

name: tex
description: Compile a DVI document from TeX source files. More information: <https://www.tug.org/begin.html>.

name: tex-fmt
description: Format LaTeX source code. More information: <https://github.com/WGUNDERWOOD/tex-fmt>.

name: texcount

name: texdoc
description: Search for appropriate documentation for (La)TeX commands or packages. More information: <https://manned.org/texdoc>.

name: texliveonfly
description: Downloads missing TeX Live packages while compiling `.tex` files. More information: <https://ctan.org/tex-archive/support/texliveonfly>.

name: textql
description: Execute SQL against structured text like CSV or TSV files. More information: <https://github.com/dinedal/textql#usage>.

name: textutil
description: Manipulate text files of various formats. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/textutil.1.html>.

name: tftp
description: Trivial File Transfer Protocol client. More information: <https://manned.org/tftp>.

name: tgatoppm
description: Convert a TrueVision Targa file to a Netpbm image. More information: <https://netpbm.sourceforge.net/doc/tgatoppm.html>.

name: tgcloud
description: Manage a Telegram account. See also: `tgsend`, `tginfo`, `tgutil`. More information: <https://pypi.org/project/telegram-cloud/>.

name: tginfo
description: Manage a Telegram account. See also: `tgcloud`, `tgsend`, `tgutil`. More information: <https://pypi.org/project/telegram-cloud/>.

name: tgpt
description: Talk to an AI chatbot without the need for API keys. Available providers: `openai`, `opengpts`, `koboldai`, `phind`, `llama2`, `blackboxai`. More information: <https://github.com/aandrew-me/tgpt>.

name: tgsend
description: Manage a Telegram account. See also: `tgcloud`, `tginfo`, `tgutil`. More information: <https://pypi.org/project/telegram-cloud/>.

name: tgutil
description: Manage a Telegram account. See also: `tgcloud`, `tgsend`, `tginfo`. More information: <https://pypi.org/project/telegram-cloud/>.

name: theharvester
description: A tool designed to be used in the early stages of a penetration test. More information: <https://github.com/laramies/theHarvester>.

name: then
description: This shell keyword is used in combination with `if` and `elif` to separate branches and branch conditions.

name: thinkjettopbm
description: Convert a HP ThinkJet printer commands file to a PBM file. More information: <https://netpbm.sourceforge.net/doc/thinkjettopbm.html>.

name: thunar
description: Graphical file manager for XFCE desktop environments. See also: `caja`, `dolphin`, `nautilus`, `mc`. More information: <https://docs.xfce.org/xfce/thunar/start>.

name: thunderbird
description: Email client and RSS reader. More information: <https://manned.org/thunderbird>.

name: tic
description: Compile terminfo and install for ncurses. More information: <https://manned.org/tic>.

name: tidy
description: Clean up and pretty print HTML, XHTML, and XML files. Note: `tidy` cannot preserve original indentation. More information: <https://api.html-tidy.org/tidy/tidylib_api_next/group__options__cli.html#gad7a9fcaf7b2a712a82e625e84c042b28>.

name: tifftopnm
description: Convert a TIFF image to a PNM image. More information: <https://netpbm.sourceforge.net/doc/tifftopnm.html>.

name: tig
description: A configurable `ncurses`-based TUI for Git. See also: `gitui`, `git-gui`. More information: <https://jonas.github.io/tig/doc/manual.html>.

name: time
description: Measure how long a command took to run. Note: `time` can either exist as a shell builtin, a standalone program, or both. See also: `times`. More information: <https://manned.org/time>.

name: timed
description: Service that synchronizes system time (e.g. using NTP). It should not be invoked manually. More information: <https://keith.github.io/xcode-man-pages/timed.8.html>.

name: timedatectl
description: Control the system time and date. More information: <https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/timedatectl.html>.

name: timeout
description: Run a command with a time limit. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/timeout-invocation.html>.

name: times
description: Print the cumulative CPU usage time of the current shell. First line is current shell CPU usage for User and System. Second is all child processes. See also: `time`. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#index-times>.

name: timeshift
description: System restore utility. More information: <https://manned.org/timeshift>.

name: timetrap
description: Simple time tracker written in Ruby. More information: <https://github.com/samg/timetrap>.

name: timew
description: A time tracking tool used to measure the duration of activities. More information: <https://timewarrior.net/docs/>.

name: timg
description: A terminal image and video viewer. More information: <https://github.com/hzeller/timg#synopsis>.

name: timidity
description: Play and convert MIDI files. More information: <https://manned.org/timidity>.

name: title
description: Set the title of the command prompt window. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/title>.

name: tldr
description: Display simple help pages for command-line tools from the tldr-pages project. Note: The `--language` and `--list` options are not required by the client specification, but most clients implement them. More information: <https://github.com/tldr-pages/tldr/blob/main/CLIENT-SPECIFICATION.md#command-line-interface>.

name: tldr-lint
description: Lint and format `tldr` pages. Note: `tldrl` can be used as an alias for `tldr-lint`. More information: <https://github.com/tldr-pages/tldr-lint#usage>.

name: tldrl
description: This command is an alias of `tldr-lint`.

name: tlmgr
description: Manage packages and configuration options of an existing TeX Live installation. Some subcommands such as `paper` have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#NAME>.

name: tlmgr-arch
description: This command is an alias of `tlmgr platform`.

name: tlmgr-backup
description: Manage backups of TeX Live packages. The default backup directory is specified by the `backupdir` option, and can be obtained with `tlmgr option`. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#backup>.

name: tlmgr-candidates
description: Get available candidate repositories from which a TeX Live package can be installed. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#candidates-pkg>.

name: tlmgr-check
description: Check the consistency of a TeX Live installation. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#check-option...-depends-executes-files-runfiles-texmfdbs-all>.

name: tlmgr-conf
description: Manage the TeX Live configuration. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#conf>.

name: tlmgr-dump-tlpdb
description: Dump the TeX Live package database. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#dump-tlpdb-option...---json>.

name: tlmgr-generate
description: Remake configuration files from information stored locally. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#generate>.

name: tlmgr-gui
description: Start a graphical user interface for `tlmgr`. `tlmgr gui` depends on the package `perl-tk`, which has to be installed manually. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#gui>.

name: tlmgr-info
description: Show information about TeX Live packages. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#info>.

name: tlmgr-install
description: Install TeX Live packages. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#install-option...-pkg>.

name: tlmgr-key
description: Manage GPG keys used to verify TeX Live databases. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#key>.

name: tlmgr-option
description: TeX Live settings manager. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#option>.

name: tlmgr-paper
description: Manage paper size options of an TeX Live installation. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#paper>.

name: tlmgr-path
description: Add or remove symlinks for TeX Live executables, man pages and info pages. This command has to be re-run for files added in the future. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#path>.

name: tlmgr-pinning
description: The pinning action manages the pinning file. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#pinning>.

name: tlmgr-platform
description: Manage TeX Live platforms. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#platform>.

name: tlmgr-recreate-tlpdb
description: Recreate the TeX Live package database. This command has a lack of documentation and should be used with caution. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/tlmgr.html>.

name: tlmgr-remove
description: Uninstall TeX Live packages. By default, removed packages will be backed up to `./tlpkg/backups` under the TL installation directory. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#remove-option...-pkg>.

name: tlmgr-repository
description: Manage repositories of a TeX Live installation. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#repository>.

name: tlmgr-restore
description: Restore package backups created with `tlmgr backup`. The default backup directory is specified by the `backupdir` option, and can be obtained with `tlmgr option`. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#restore>.

name: tlmgr-search
description: Search for TeX Live packages using (Perl) `regex`. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#search>.

name: tlmgr-shell
description: Start an interactive shell of the native TeX Live manager. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#shell>.

name: tlmgr-update
description: Update TeX Live packages. More information: <https://www.tug.org/texlive/doc/tlmgr.html#update-option...-pkg>.

name: tlp
description: Advanced power management for Linux. See also: `tlp-stat`. More information: <https://linrunner.de/tlp/usage/tlp.html>.

name: tlp-stat
description: Generate TLP status reports. See also: `tlp`. More information: <https://linrunner.de/tlp/usage/tlp-stat>.

name: tmpmail
description: A temporary email right from your terminal written in POSIX sh. More information: <https://github.com/sdushantha/tmpmail#usage>.

name: tmsu
description: Simple tool for tagging files. More information: <https://tmsu.org/>.

name: tmt
description: Test Management Tool for creating, running, and debugging tests. Some subcommands such as `run`, `try`, etc. have their own usage documentation. More information: <https://tmt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/examples.html>.

name: tmt-run
description: Execute `tmt` test steps. By default, all steps are run. More information: <https://tmt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/stories/cli.html#run>.

name: tmt-try
description: Quickly experiment with tests and environments. More information: <https://tmt.readthedocs.io/en/stable/stories/cli.html#try>.

name: tmutil

name: tmux
description: Terminal multiplexer. It allows multiple sessions with windows, panes, and more. See also: `zellij`, `screen`. More information: <https://github.com/tmux/tmux>.

name: tmuxinator
description: Create and manage tmux sessions easily. More information: <https://manned.org/tmuxinator>.

name: tod
description: A tiny Todoist client in Rust. It takes simple input and dumps it in your inbox or another project. Taking advantage of natural language processing to assign due dates, tags, etc. More information: <https://github.com/tod-org/tod/blob/main/docs/usage.md#usage>.

name: todo
description: A simple, standards-based, cli todo manager. More information: <https://todoman.readthedocs.io/en/stable/man.html>.

name: todo.sh
description: Simple and extensible shell script for managing your `todo.txt` file. More information: <https://github.com/todotxt/todo.txt-cli>.

name: todoist
description: Access <https://todoist.com> from the command-line. More information: <https://github.com/sachaos/todoist#usage>.

name: todoman
description: This command is an alias of `todo`.

name: tofu-output
description: Export structured data about your OpenTofu resources. More information: <https://opentofu.org/docs/cli/commands/output/>.

name: tofu-plan
description: Generate and show OpenTofu execution plans. More information: <https://opentofu.org/docs/cli/commands/plan/>.

name: toilet

name: toipe
description: Yet another typing test, but crab flavored. A trusty terminal typing tester. More information: <https://github.com/Samyak2/toipe>.

name: tokei
description: Display statistics about code. More information: <https://github.com/XAMPPRocky/tokei>.

name: tomb
description: Manage encrypted storage directories that can be safely transported and hidden in a filesystem. More information: <https://dyne.org/docs/tomb/manpage/>.

name: toolbox

name: toolbox-create
description: Create a new Toolbx container. More information: <https://manned.org/toolbox-create>.

name: toolbox-enter
description: Enter a Toolbx container for interactive use. See also: `toolbox run`. More information: <https://manned.org/toolbox-enter>.

name: toolbox-help
description: Display help information about Toolbx. More information: <https://manned.org/toolbox-help>.

name: toolbox-init-container

name: toolbox-rm

name: toolbox-run
description: Run a command in an existing Toolbx container. See also: `toolbox enter`. More information: <https://manned.org/toolbox-run>.

name: top

name: topgrade
description: Update all applications on the system. More information: <https://github.com/r-darwish/topgrade>.

name: topydo
description: A to-do list application that uses the todo.txt format. More information: <https://github.com/topydo/topydo>.

name: tor

name: torify

name: torsocks
description: Route the traffic of any application through the Tor network. Note: `torsocks` will assume that it should connect to the Tor SOCKS proxy running at 127.0.0.1:9050 being the defaults of the Tor daemon. More information: <https://manned.org/torsocks>.

name: touch

name: tox

name: toybox
description: Multipurpose tool that provides many standard Unix utilities. Commonly used in Android and embedded Linux systems. More information: <https://landley.net/toybox/>.

name: tpp
description: Command-Line based presentation tool. More information: <https://manned.org/tpp>.

name: tput
description: View and modify terminal settings and capabilities. More information: <https://manned.org/tput>.

name: tqdm
description: Show progress over time of a command. More information: <https://tqdm.github.io/docs/cli/>.

name: tr
description: Translate characters: run replacements based on single characters and character sets. More information: <https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tr-invocation.html>.

name: trace-cmd-list
description: Show available tracers, events, or options for tracing. See also: `trace-cmd record`, `trace-cmd report`. More information: <https://manned.org/trace-cmd-list>.

name: trace-cmd-record

name: trace-cmd-report

name: tracert
description: Receive information about each step in the route between your PC and the target. More information: <https://learn.microsoft.com/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/tracert>.

name: traefik
description: An HTTP reverse proxy and load balancer. More information: <https://doc.traefik.io/traefik/v2.11/operations/cli/>.

name: trafilatura

name: trans
description: Translate Shell, a command-line translator. More information: <https://github.com/soimort/translate-shell>.

name: transcode
description: Transcode video and audio codecs, and convert between media formats. More information: <https://manned.org/transcode>.

name: transcrypt
description: Transparently encrypt files within a Git repository. More information: <https://github.com/elasticdog/transcrypt#command-line-options>.

name: transfersh
description: An unofficial client for transfer.sh. More information: <https://github.com/AlpixTM/transfersh>.

name: translationd
description: Enables Translation features. It should not be invoked manually.

name: transmission

name: transmission-cli
description: A lightweight, command-line BitTorrent client. This tool has been deprecated, please see `transmission-remote`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-cli>.

name: transmission-create
description: Create BitTorrent `.torrent` files. See also: `transmission`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-create>.

name: transmission-daemon
description: Daemon controlled with `transmission-remote` or its web interface. See also: `transmission`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-daemon>.

name: transmission-edit
description: Modify announce URLs from torrent files. See also: `transmission`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-edit>.

name: transmission-remote
description: Remote control utility for `transmission-daemon` and `transmission`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-remote>.

name: transmission-show
description: Get information about a torrent file. See also: `transmission`. More information: <https://manned.org/transmission-show>.

name: transport
description: Manage line transport protocols. Accessed in configuration mode under `line`. More information: <https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/routers/sdwan/command/iosxe/qualified-cli-command-reference-guide/m-line-commands.pdf>.

name: trap
description: Execute a command upon an event. More information: <https://manned.org/trap.1posix>.

name: trash
description: Manage the trashcan/recycling bin. More information: <https://github.com/andreafrancia/trash-cli>.

name: trash-cli
description: This command is an alias of `trash`.

name: trash-empty
description: This command has been moved to `trash`.

name: trash-list
description: This command has been moved to `trash`.

name: trash-put
description: This command is an alias of `trash`.

name: trash-restore
description: This command has been moved to `trash`.

name: trash-rm
description: This command has been moved to `trash`.

name: trashy
description: An alternative to `rm` and `trash-cli` written in Rust. More information: <https://github.com/oberblastmeister/trashy#usage>.

name: travis
description: Interface with Travis CI. More information: <https://github.com/travis-ci/travis.rb#command-line-client>.

name: trawl
description: Print out network interface information to the console, much like ifconfig/ipconfig/ip/ifdata. More information: <https://github.com/robphoenix/trawl>.

name: trayer

name: trdsql
description: Execute SQL on CSV, LTSV, JSON, YAML, and TBLN files. More information: <https://noborus.github.io/trdsql/>.

name: tre

name: tred
description: Compute the transitive reduction of directed graphs. Graphviz filters: `acyclic`, `bcomps`, `comps`, `edgepaint`, `gvcolor`, `gvpack`, `mingle`, `nop`, `sccmap`, `tred`, & `unflatten`. More information: <https://www.graphviz.org/pdf/tred.1.pdf>.

name: tree
description: Show the contents of the current directory as a tree. More information: <https://manned.org/tree>.

name: treemd
description: View markdown files with tree-based navigation and an interactive TUI. More information: <https://github.com/Epistates/treemd#usage>.

name: treetime
description: TreeTime provides routines for ancestral sequence reconstruction and inference of molecular-clock phylogenies. More information: <https://treetime.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials.html>.

name: trip

name: trivy
description: Scanner for vulnerabilities in container images, file systems, and Git repositories, as well as for configuration issues. More information: <https://trivy.dev/docs/latest/guide/references/configuration/cli/trivy/>.

name: trizen
description: Arch Linux utility for building packages from the Arch User Repository (AUR). More information: <https://github.com/trizen/trizen/blob/master/TRIZEN.md>.

name: troff
description: Typesetting processor for the groff (GNU Troff) document formatting system. See also: `groff`. More information: <https://manned.org/troff>.

name: true

name: truffle
description: Develop smart contracts for running services on the Ethereum blockchain. More information: <https://archive.trufflesuite.com/docs/truffle/reference/truffle-commands/>.

name: trufflehog

name: truncate

name: trunk

name: trunk.io
description: Run linters, formatters, and security analyzers on code. More information: <https://docs.trunk.io/code-quality/overview/getting-started/commands-reference>.

name: trunk.rs
description: Bundle and serve Rust WASM web applications. More information: <https://trunkrs.dev/commands/>.

name: truss
description: Troubleshooting tool for tracing system calls. SunOS equivalent of strace. More information: <https://www.unix.com/man-page/linux/1/truss>.

name: trust
description: Operate on the trust policy store. More information: <https://manned.org/trust>.

name: ts
description: Add timestamps to every line from `stdin`. More information: <https://manned.org/ts>.

name: ts-node

name: tsc

name: tshark

name: tsort
